explanation:
- MHD_destroy_response: needed to determine whether the call can return normally (or is annotated noreturn / contains __builtin_unreachable). If it does not return, statements after calls (e.g. resp_single = NULL, loop continuation) could be unreachable.
- resp_single: its declaration/definition (type, storage, initialization) is required to decide whether the if (NULL != resp_single) test is a compile-time constant (which would make the enclosed call/jump unconditional or dead), and to rule out macro aliases that could make code unreachable.
- resps: the declaration/definition is required to determine whether the resps pointer and its lifetime/definition make the loop body reachable (e.g. if resps is a constant NULL or a compile-time-empty array), and to check for macro/aliasing that could render the loop unreachable.
- num_resps: required to see whether the loop bound is a compile-time constant (e.g. zero) making the for-loop body unreachable, or whether it can be non-zero at runtime.
- body_dyn: its declaration/definition/initialization is required to determine whether the if (NULL != body_dyn) test is compile-time constant (which would make the free call and subsequent assignment unreachable).
